06385nmm a2200793Ia 9781479844401DE-B159720240328111612.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240328t20162016nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97814798444017 a10.18574/nyu/9781479844401.001.00012doi  a(DE-B1597)681133  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 7aPHI0260002bisacsh00aTime :bA Vocabulary of the Present /ced. by Amy Elias, Joel Burges. 1aNew York, NY : bNew York University Press, c[2016] 4c©2016  a1 online resource :b28 black and white illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: Time Studies Today -- tPart I: Time as History -- t1 Past / Future -- t2 Extinction / Adaptation -- t3 Modern / Altermodern -- t4 Obsolescence / Innovation -- t5 Anticipation / Unexpected -- tPart II: Time as Calculation -- t6 Clock / Lived -- t7 Synchronic / Anachronic -- t8 Human / Planetary -- t9 Serial / Simultaneous -- t10 Emergency / Everyday -- t11 Labor / Leisure -- t12 Real / Quality -- tPart III: Time as Culture -- t13 Aesthetic / Prosthetic -- t14 Analepsis / Prolepsis -- t15 Embodied / Disembodied -- t16 Theological / Worldly -- t17 Authentic / Artificial -- t18 Batch / Interactive -- t19 Transmission / Influence -- t20 Silence / Beat -- tTime Studies: A Bibliographical Reading List -- tAbout the Contributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe critical condition and historical motivation behind Time Studies The concept of time in the post-millennial age is undergoing a radical rethinking within the humanities. Time: A Vocabulary of the Present newly theorizes our experiences of time in relation to developments in post-1945 cultural theory and arts practices. Wide ranging and theoretically provocative, the volume introduces readers to cutting-edge temporal conceptualizations and investigates what exactly constitutes the scope of time studies.Featuring twenty essays that reveal what we talk about when we talk about time today, especially in the areas of history, measurement, and culture, each essay pairs two keywords to explore the tension and nuances between them, from “past/future” and “anticipation/unexpected” to “extinction/adaptation” and “serial/simultaneous.” Moving beyond the truisms of postmodernism, the collection newly theorizes the meanings of temporality in relationship to aesthetic, cultural, technological, and economic developments in the postwar period. This book thus assumes that time—not space, as the postmoderns had it—is central to the contemporary period, and that through it we can come to terms with what contemporaneity can be for human beings caught up in the historical present. In the end, Time reveals that the present is a cultural matrix in which overlapping temporalities condition and compete for our attention. Thus each pair of terms presents two temporalities, yielding a generative account of the time, or times, in which we live.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2024) 7aPHILOSOPHY / Criticism.2bisacsh1 aAnable, Aubrey, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAnderson, Ben, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBurges, Joel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBurges, Joel, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aCanales, Jimena, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCurrie, Mark, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aElias, Amy J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aElias, Amy, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aFreeman, Elizabeth, econtribut